default• What will the local environmental impact (for example air pollution) be from the use heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?
defaultCHP engines are also less clean than
default burning gas. Highly dependent on good quality maintenance and quality of fuel being consumed, and on operating set up where efficiency and cleanliness are mutually incompatible. A key aspect on the suitability of CHP is the utilisation of heat. In our exp
defaulterience, CHP engines are too quickly specified for demand that is too high. This is also incompatible with the “primary directive” of reduced consumption.
default A major oversight in many CHP assessments that also leads to 
defaultexcessive pollution is that the
default heat dem
defaultand is done in advance of any heat capture and re-use. Many facilities by virtue of the operation dynamics do require heating and cooling simultaneously. By using heatpumps to capture waste heat and deliver for consumption the demand falls again. Sadly how
defaultever as heat capture and re-use is not considered in advance of CHP specification the CHP heat demand is over stated resulting in either sub economic operation of the CHP unit, or sub-economic IN-operation of the CHP unit.
default A well designed building should h
defaultave no fuel combustion during late spring, autumn and summer as any air conditioning is a viable source for heating to 65C or thereabouts.
default• What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity pr
defaultoduction plus domestic heat pumps? 
defaultThis is a very closed question implying these are the only two options. However taking these two options, gas for space heating results in a thermal conversion of around 85% less distribution losses in the gas network. T
defaulthe network exists and is simple to extend. Similarly, local domestic heatpumps can be added and depending on the quality of the installation can decentralize heat. 
defaultOther ideas though that need to be borne in mind are the emergence of domestic CHP and dome
defaultstic fuel cells. I personally expect a 
default“
defaultgas to electricity and heat
default”
default format to prevail in a domestic setting as whilst I am a heatpump supporter, unless the target is zero carbon heat then the use of 
defaultdomestic heatpumps seems challenging. Not least of all a
defaults I’m quite worried about the widespread dispersion of HFC heatpumps which invariable reach 
defaulta 
defaultpoint of gas leakage of the very high Global Warming gases they use. 
defaultLarger heatpumps use zero GWP fluids.
defaultOn a more networked scale district heating sourced with
default the low grade heat from the power plant (they are rarely more than 50% efficient so 1Gwe
default = 1GWth at circa 30C) is a viable source that can be delivered in a district network.
